    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-03-17T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-03-17T18:00:00-05:00" n="516"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d516">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">511.4A6/235: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-17T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 17, 1931—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>31. Department’s telegram, July 22, 1930.<note n="89" xml:id="d516fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> Inform the Secretary General of the League of Nations, in
                    reply to his note of June 14, 1930,<note n="89" xml:id="d516fn2">Not
                        printed.</note> that this Government accepts the invitation to participate
                    in the conference on the limitation of the manufacture of narcotic drugs to be
                    held on May 27, 1931, and that the delegates will be John K. Caldwell, Chairman;
                    Harry J. Anslinger (Commissioner of Narcotics); Dr. Walter Lewis Treadway
                    (Assistant Surgeon General, Chief, Division of Mental Hygiene); and Sanborn
                    Young, a member of the Senate of the State of California.</p>
                <p>The Department desires that Winthrop Greene<note n="90" xml:id="d516fn3">Third
                        Secretary of Legation in Switzerland.</note> act as Secretary and Vice
                    Consul Smith<note n="91" xml:id="d516fn4">Marc Smith, at Geneva.</note> act as
                    disbursing officer of the delegation. Names of technical and clerical assistants
                    will be communicated later.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
